title: Wawawai Landing TT & Wawawai Grade Hill Climb
description:
Roads are chip-sealed and in fair to good condition.

The 20K TT is flat and it will be an out-and-back.  First rider starts at 11:00 a.m. 

The ITT hill climb (11K) will start at 1:45.  Juniors are highly encouraged to do this event.

The hill climb (11K) will be a mass start race and start at 2:00 p.m.  

Awards will be given out to all categories based on the combined times of the two events.  You can do only one event, but you will not be eligible for awards.
course: ourses: 20K flat TT, and a hill climb up the Wawawai grade - approximately 11K with 1950+ feet of climbing
registration:
Costs: $20 per race.  USAC license required to race.   One day license for category 5 men and 4 women is $10 and available at the race. To race in category 3 races and above you must have a USCF annual license ($60), which can be purchased at www.usacycling.org.

Online registration will be available as well as on the day of the race.
notes:
Roads are chip-sealed and in fair to good condition.

The 20K TT is flat and it will be an out-and-back.  First rider starts at 11:00 a.m.

title: Tour de Dung #1
description: Tour De Dung Road Race #1: March 16th 2013. PRESENTED BY: THE GARAGE AND AUDI CYCLING TEAMS First of two races in the rain shadow of the beautiful Olympic Mountain Range. Start/finish is across the road from the Dungeness State Park and Recreation Area
course: COURSE: Very flat fast good surfaced course (2-3 rollers) but wind frequently has been a factor usually out of the west between 10 to 20 mph. Course is the same as in years past. Finish will be on Kitchen Dick Rd.For Map see http://connect.garmin.com/course/640230#.Tz2jA_FlDnY.email
registration:
Registration: Each race $30 which includes Washington State Taxes. Registration opens at 8:45 AM and closes 15 minutes prior to the start of your race. Annual USA Cycling Licenses ONLY: One day licenses for Cat 5 Men and Cat 4 Women only. WSBA numbers: Will be used and can be purchased at www.wsbaracing.com (not for sale at the race). Rental numbers: Will be available at the race for a $10 rental fee ($5 is refundable). For out-of-state riders there is no fee to rent a number just a $5 deposit. 
In order for specific Women Cat 4A & Woman Beginner, i.e. Cat 4B, fields to be offered a Minimum field size of 20 for Women Cat 4A & Women Cat 4B fields must be pre-registered by 3/12. Pre-registered field sizes not met will result in a combination of these two fields to be run at the 10am time and will cancel the mentor/clinics as listed.
notes: Parking and porta-lets will be located in the field across the road from the Dungeness State Park and Recreation Area. RACE NUMBERS: WSBA numbers on the LEFT hand side of jerseys and on frame. More race and Prize details will be posted closer to event on http://racing.garagebilliards.com/
directions: LOCATION: Sequim, Dungeness, Washington. From Seattle using the Bainbridge Island Ferry: Exit the ferry at Winslow. Stay on SR 305 to Poulsbo. Proceed through Poulsbo and take SR 3 north (follow signs to the Hood Canal Bridge). Follow directions from Hood Canal Bridge. From the Edmunds-Kingston Ferry: Remain on SR 104 the Canal Bridge. Follow directions from Hood Canal Bridge. From Tacoma: Take SR 16 from the Tacoma Narrows Bridge north. At the junction with SR 3, take SR 3 north to the Hood Canal Bridge. Directions from Hood Canal Bridge: At the Hood Canal Bridge, make a left turn (right turn if you are coming from Kingston) and proceed across the bridge (on SR 104). Follow SR 104 to the junction with US Hwy 101. Take US 101 North toward Pt. Townsend and Pt. Angeles. Follow US 101 past Sequim, stay on Highway 101 until you reach Kitchen Dick Road, take a right onto Kitchen Dick Road. Continue on Kitchen Dick Road, past Woodcock when you will be on the race course, all the way to Lotzgesell Road Rd where the parking area and Start/Finish location. From Olympia and South: Take US Hwy 101 north. Follow US 101 past Sequim, stay on Highway 101 until you reach Kitchen Dick Road, take a right onto Kitchen Dick Road. Continue on Kitchen Dick Road, past Woodcock when you will be on the race course, all the way to Lotzgesell Road Rd where the parking area and Start/Finish location

title: The Little 150
description: The Little 150 is a unique road race possessing a blend of teamwork, road endurance fitness, track racing power, and enjoyment for spectators and racers alike. With deference to the revered Little 500 at Indiana University, we have modified their format because we don\'t all enjoy racing in cinder on our friend\'s single speed, track bike. That said, the appeal of bonding with some buddies and trying to rip the legs off your competitors is what we are all about at the Little 150. Bring your fastest road bike, a head wired with racing strategy, a few good teammates and put some hurt on. Your team can be composed of 2-5 racers.
course: The Little 150 utilizes the \"flat\" course at Pacific Raceway with team exchanges made in pit road. This course is a closed road, very open and provides great racing as you are not yellow line controlled.
registration:
Register on USA Cycling, there will be no day of registration available. Register by 6/28/13!
PLEASE, provide you team name by updating your \"chip number\" in USA Cycling. To find \"chip number\", login to USA Cycling, go to Account, choose \"account\", in account information edit the chip number for \"custom\". Please put your team name in the cell provided.

title: Pacific Raceways Kermesse
description: The Pacific Raceways Kermesse series is a 2013 Washington State Kermesse Cup event. The Washington Kermesse Cup is a series of events evoke the Belgian tradition of short, fast and hard races and include dirt sections similar to the cobbles of Belgium. The race is a circuit that mixes paved road and hard-pack dirt. The dirt section is rated GENTLE. Registration and finish are on the PR Track.  Races will run counter clockwise laps of the PR Flats using the paved straight away and the old service road
course:
The course will use the "flats" section of PR with the service road that runs behind the bleachers.  Total distance is approximately two miles.  
The dirt section is rated easy to moderate difficulty.  Races will run counter-clockwise laps.
registration: Registration will be at the parking area. Online at USACycling.org or day of at the Pacific Raceways. Registration closes 20 minutes before the start of each event. The online entry fee includes $3 per rider per day for USA Cycling insurance. A current year USA Cycling Rider Waiver and Release form must be signed by the participant and, if under 18, by the parent or legal guardian.
notes:
To enter any race for Men Cat 4 and above or Women Cat 3 and above a USAC annual license must be presented. Purchase online at USACycling.org (not for sale at the race). All beginners (Cat 5 Men, Cat 4 Women) may race on one-day license. No exceptions. OBRA riders of any category other than Beginner must present a valid USAC license. Foreign riders must purchase one-day license or present proof of out-of-country insurance. One-day licenses are $10, available at the race.

WSBA numbers will be used. The officials request that both bib numbers be clearly visible placed parallel with your jerseys side seam on the back and above the pockets. Frame number should be attached per WSBA instructions. Examples of proper placement: http://gcracingllc.com/numberplacement.aspx. Rental numbers are available for a $10 fee ($5 refundable). For out-of-state riders a $5 number refundable deposit will be assessed.
directions: Pacific Raceways is located approx 40 minutes south of Seattle and 25 minutes north of Tacoma in Kent.  	Map to: 31001 144th Ave SE  Kent, WA 98042

title: Ronde Ohop
description:
The Ronde Ohop is the longest running Roubaix / Kermesse race in Washington State.  First run in 2005 the race mixes paved road sections and hard-pack dirt sectors evocative of the cobbles of belgium.

fast and hard races. Running through rural Eatonville and the local parks the race runs on good county roads with 13 total miles of dirt road.
course: Race starts at Mashel Loop field. Races will cover 2 to 4 laps of the 6 mile Eatonville Loop circuit (all paved) then 10 laps of the Mashel Loop (the Mashel Loop is 1 mile road, 1.25 mile dirt). Course map & profiles can be found at http://www.mapmyride.com/routes/view/18148494
registration:
Online at USACycling or day of at the Mashel Loop. Registration closes 20 minutes before the start of each event. The entry fee includes $3 per rider per day for USA Cycling insurance. A current year USA Cycling Rider Waiver and Release form must be signed by the participant and, if under 18, by the parent or legal guardian.

To enter any race for Men Cat 4 and above or Women Cat 3 and above a USAC annual license must be presented. Purchase online at USACycling.org (not for sale at the race). All beginners (Cat 5 Men, Cat 4 Women) may race on one-day license. No exceptions. OBRA riders of any category other than Beginner must present a valid USAC license. Foreign riders must purchase one-day license or present proof of out-of-country insurance. One-day licenses are $10, available at the race.
notes:
WSBA numbers will be used. The officials request that both bib numbers be clearly visible placed parallel with your jerseys side seam on the back and above the pockets. Frame number should be attached per WSBA instructions. Examples of proper placement: http://gcracingllc.com/numberplacement.aspx. Rental numbers are available for a $10 fee ($5 refundable). For out-of-state riders a $5 number refundable deposit will be assessed.

Neutral wheel support will be provided. In addition to two neutral wheel pits, there will be two additional wheels in/wheels out pits on the course for a total of three wheel pits on the Mashel Loop. The organizer is not responsible for wheels or equipment left at the race.

Results will be posted at registration. Results become final 15 minutes after posting. Questions concerning results should be directed to the Chief Judge at the Finish line.
directions: Parking will be at the Nisqually- Mashel State Park on the right under the power lines. From North or South on I-5 Take exit 127. Drive east on Hwy 512 for two miles, then take the Pacific Ave./Mt. Rainier exit south. Follow Pacific Ave. about five miles to where the road splits in a "Y." Follow signs for Mt. Rainier (the left branch of the fork) taking Hwy 7 south. Drive about 17 miles, passing Ohop Valley Rd. At the top of the long sweeping hill turn right onto the Mashel Prairie Road on the right side. Go about  of a mile and park on the right side under the power lines
